      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yep. The app data gets wrapped in TCP, IP, and link-layer information, so the sent packet is bigger than the photo chunk.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Count headers"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The image size matters to the CMS, but the network problem is about what gets sent after headers are added.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Count pixels"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Retries can add traffic, but this screen is showing one packet getting bigger because each layer adds control info.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Count retries"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Compression might change the image body, but it does not explain the TCP, IP, and Ethernet bytes shown here.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Count compression"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What should we include in the size check?"
    },
    {
      "context": "The browser only knows `api.acme-cms.com`, {{NAME}}. This VPN gateway is choosing `lte-tunnel` for that API subnet, one hop at a time. If we yell at the CMS first, it will just sit there looking innocent.",
      "imagePrompt": "Close-up of a network admin screen with a traceroute and a tiny route table. Visible text: `Trace to api.acme-cms.com`, `1 store-router`, `2 vpn-gateway`, `3 lte-tunnel`. Route table line highlighted: `203.0.113.0/24 → lte-tunnel`. Another line says `0.0.0.0/0 → fiber-wan`.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Right. Each router makes its own next-hop choice, and this gateway is clearly sending the API subnet into the LTE tunnel.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Gateway route"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "DNS helped find the API address, but this screen already has the route decision. The gateway’s table is the next place to fix.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "DNS record"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The CMS template does not decide which network hop packets take. The highlighted route line does.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "CMS template"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The fiber link is the default route, but the API subnet has a more specific route to LTE. That specific route wins here.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Fiber default"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Where should we inspect the next hop?"
    },
    {
      "context": "Small packets reach the API. Bigger ones hit the LTE tunnel and complain about fragmentation. So the path is not totally broken; it is picky about packet size.",
      "imagePrompt": "A centered terminal-style path MTU test table. Columns: `Total IP size`, `DF set`, `Result`. Rows: `1380`, `yes`, `OK`; `1400`, `yes`, `OK`; `1420`, `yes`, `Fragmentation needed`; `1500`, `yes`, `Timeout`. A badge reads `LTE tunnel path`.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "That fits the table. Packets up to about 1400 get through, and larger ones fail when they cannot fragment.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "MTU about 1400"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "A bad password would fail small and large requests the same way. Here, size is the pattern.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Bad password"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The database might be slow later, but these packets are failing before the API can handle the upload.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Slow database"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "DNS is already resolving because the test reaches the same API path with smaller packets.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Expired DNS"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What is the path telling us?"
    },
    {
      "context": "Fragmenting gets us halfway, then the firewall drops the later piece. Since the destination has to reassemble the pieces, one missing piece means the upload is toast.",
      "imagePrompt": "Close-up of a firewall log for one large upload packet. Three short rows are visible: `IP ID 77A3 fragment 1 PASS`, `IP ID 77A3 fragment 2 DROP: non-initial fragment`, `Destination reassembly: incomplete`. A small warning icon sits beside the dropped row.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly. If we keep packets small enough, they do not need to fragment, so the firewall never gets a loose fragment to drop.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Send smaller segments"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Allowing every fragment is risky and still fragile. Better is to avoid fragmentation by sending smaller TCP segments.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Allow all fragments"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "TLS is not the reason the second fragment is dropped. The packet size and fragmentation are the issue.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Turn off TLS"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The file name will not change how IP fragments travel. We need smaller packets on this path.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Rename photos"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Best fix for this path?"
    },
    {
      "context": "We can leave LTE up for launch and make TCP send smaller chunks. Tunnel MTU is 1400, and IP plus TCP headers take 40 bytes before the data.",
      "imagePrompt": "Close-up of a VPN settings panel. Visible fields: `Tunnel MTU: 1400`, `IP header: 20 B`, `TCP header: 20 B`, `TCP MSS clamp: ____ B`. A note under the blank says `MSS = data inside the TCP segment`.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. 1400 minus 20 bytes of IP header and 20 bytes of TCP header leaves 1360 bytes for TCP data.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "1360 bytes"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "1400 uses the whole tunnel MTU for data and leaves no room for the IP and TCP headers, so it would still overshoot.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "1400 bytes"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "1500 is the usual Ethernet MTU, but this LTE tunnel path is smaller. That is the number causing the trouble.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "1500 bytes"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "1472 is a familiar ping payload for a 1500-byte path, not the TCP MSS for this 1400-byte tunnel.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "1472 bytes"
        }
      ],
      "question": "Set the MSS clamp to what?"
    },
    {
      "context": "The test upload finished, and the capture shows zero fragments. Mina says the angry cheese photo finally made it to the CMS, which is apparently business-critical.",
      "imagePrompt": "A CMS upload result screen with a green check beside `angry-cheese.jpg uploaded`. Next to it is a small packet capture summary: `Max IP size: 1400`, `Fragments: 0`, `Route: lte-tunnel`. A launch checklist line says `Uploads open?` with an empty checkbox.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yep. The upload succeeds, packets stay within the path MTU, and there are no fragments to drop. Open it back up.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Reopen uploads"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Turning off the clamp would bring back the oversized packets and the dropped fragments.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Disable clamp"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The CMS just accepted the file. The network size fix is what changed the result.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Rollback CMS"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "DNS is not the remaining issue. The route works now, and the upload is complete.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Flush DNS"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What do we do next?"
    }
  ],
  "title": "The pop-up upload mystery"
}

{
  "scenario": {
    "imagePrompt": "A small neuroscience lab imaging bench with a microscope monitor in the center. On the monitor is a live cell-culture image labeled “Morning drug screen: neural wells.” A sticky note on the monitor says “Robot starts at 10:00.” Coffee cup with a nervous-looking doodle nearby.",
    "text": "I’m in the imaging room with Mina, and the drug-screen robot starts in 20 minutes. The cell counts look too neat, which is never a comforting thing before coffee.",
    "title": "Imaging bench"
  },
  "steps": [
    {
      "context": "{{NAME}}, Well A is the one slowing us down. The middle cell has a round body, lots of short branches, and one long skinny process running like a wire across the field.",
      "imagePrompt": "Close-up microscope view of a neural cell culture labeled “Well A.” One central cell has a round cell body, many short branching projections, and one very long thin projection stretching across the image toward another cell. A small arrow label says “long process.” Background has a few faint support-looking cells, but the central cell is clearly the focus.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. That long wire-like process and branching cell body fit a neuron built for sending signals. Count it as a neuron for the screen.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Count neuron"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Not this one. Glia can have branches, but this long signal-carrying process is the big clue. This cell belongs in the neuron count.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Count glia"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Debris would not have a clear body with organized branches and a long process. This is a living neuron, not microscope lint having a big day.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ignore debris"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Bacteria would look tiny and scattered, not like one large branched cell. The shape points to a neuron here.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Flag bacteria"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What should we mark first?"
    },
    {
      "context": "Okay, this next patch is different. These cells are flat and starry, and they’re tucked around the neurons like they’re running snack service, not sending the main signal.",
      "imagePrompt": "Close-up microscope view labeled “Well B support patch.” Several broad, flat, star-shaped cells surround two smaller neuron cell bodies. The star-shaped cells have many short arms but no single long axon-like wire. A green stain label in the corner reads “GFAP bright.”",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Right. Flat star-shaped cells with a glial marker are support cells. They matter, but they should not inflate the neuron count.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Tag glia"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "These are around the neurons, but they do not show a clear long axon-like process. Counting them as neurons would make the well look more mature than it is.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Tag neurons"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "They’re organized cells with a marker signal, not random junk. Better tag them as glia so the support layer is tracked correctly.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Tag debris"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "No need to stop the culture just because glia are present. The move is to tag them separately from neurons.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Stop culture"
        }
      ],
      "question": "How should we tag these cells?"
    },
    {
      "context": "Here’s the confusing one. This cell is wrapped around an axon like insulation, so it sits right on the signal line. But its job is support, not message-sending.",
      "imagePrompt": "Tight microscope-style diagram of a nerve fiber labeled “Axon with wrapping cell.” A long thin axon runs horizontally through the center. Around part of it is a segmented pale wrapping layer, with one oval nucleus sitting on the outside of the wrap. Short visible labels: “axon” on the inner fiber and “wrap” on the outer layer.",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Exactly. A cell wrapping an axon is glia doing support work, like insulation. It helps the signal move, but it is not the signal-sending neuron itself.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Mark glia"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Tempting, because it hugs the axon. But the wrapped fiber is the neuron part; the wrapping cell is support glia.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Mark neuron"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "The neat wrap and visible nucleus make it a real cell structure, not loose debris. This should be marked as glia.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Ignore debris"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "There may be one axon inside, but the outer wrapping cell is not another axon. Mark the wrapper as glia.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Add axon"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What is the wrapping cell?"
    },
    {
      "context": "This explains the too-perfect count. The software counted anything with branches as a neuron, but Well C has high GFAP and almost no spikes. That’s a support-cell party, not a working network.",
      "imagePrompt": "Cropped lab dashboard for “Well C review.” Three large readable lines: “Auto neuron-like count: 92%,” “Activity spikes: 0/min,” and “GFAP marker: HIGH.” Below is one thumbnail microscope image showing many broad star-shaped cells and only a few long thin axon-like processes. A red note says “Before drug screen?”",
      "options": [
        {
          "feedback": "Yes. Recount using shape, marker, and job clues before starting the drug screen. The auto count mixed glia into the neuron number.",
          "isCorrect": true,
          "text": "Recount manually"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Starting now would test a well that may not have enough working neurons. The mismatch says we need to reclassify first.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Start screen"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Averaging would hide the problem. Well C has a specific mismatch: high support-cell marker, low activity, and an inflated neuron-like count.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Average wells"
        },
        {
          "feedback": "Deleting the well is too quick. First confirm the cell types; if it is glia-heavy after recounting, then we can exclude it cleanly.",
          "isCorrect": false,
          "text": "Delete well"
        }
      ],
      "question": "What should we do before the screen?"
    }
  ],
  "title": "The well that looked too perfect"
}

{
